<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical freezer failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Eight failure modes account for nearly every standalone freezer call.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Freezer not freezing / temp climbing (most common).</strong> Could be condenser fan motor (year 6 to 10), evaporator fan motor, defrost system stuck-in-defrost, thermostat drift, refrigerant leak (rare residential but happens), compressor mechanical wear. Diagnostic with thermometer plus refrigerant gauges.</li>
      <li><strong>Frost building inside excessively.</strong> Defrost system failure (frost-free freezers only, manual-defrost chest freezers expected to require manual defrost periodically). Defrost timer, defrost heater, defrost termination thermostat.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor running constantly, never cycling off.</strong> Refrigerant low (leak), condenser dirty, ambient overload (garage in summer), thermostat stuck closed, or door seal leak letting warm air in.</li>
      <li><strong>Door seal failure / door not sealing.</strong> Gasket compressed flat (year 5 to 10), latch mechanism worn (chest freezers), door alignment off (upright). Replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Water on floor / leaking water.</strong> Defrost drain blocked, drain pan cracked, condensation overflow.</li>
      <li><strong>Freezer making excessive noise.</strong> Condenser fan motor bearings, evaporator fan ice contact, compressor mounting feet degraded.</li>
      <li><strong>Garage freezer not maintaining temp in extreme weather.</strong> Non-garage-rated freezer in garage installation. Solution: garage-rated freezer kit (some models) or replacement with garage-rated unit.</li>
      <li><strong>Light not working / display issues (upright freezers).</strong> Bulb replacement, display board failure.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ARCHITECTURE -->
<section class="section">
