    <h2 class="section-title">Chest vs upright vs garage-rated.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Chest Freezer</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Top-opening lid, horizontal storage</li>
      <li>Most efficient (cold air doesn't escape when opened, settles back)</li>
      <li>Best for bulk frozen storage (whole quarters of beef, freezer meals batch)</li>
      <li>Common sizes: 5 to 25 cu ft</li>
      <li>Manual defrost typical (frost-free chest freezers exist but less common)</li>
      <li>Top brands: Frigidaire (FFCS series), GE (FCM series), Whirlpool (WZC series), Magic Chef, Kenmore</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Upright Freezer</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Vertical orientation, like a refrigerator with freezer section only</li>
      <li>Easier to organize (shelves, drawers, door storage)</li>
      <li>Less energy efficient than chest (cold air falls out when door opens)</li>
      <li>Common sizes: 13 to 22 cu ft</li>
      <li>Frost-free typical</li>
      <li>Top brands: Frigidaire (FFFU series), Whirlpool (WZF series), GE (FUF series), Maytag (MZF series), Kenmore. Plus premium standalone freezer columns from Sub-Zero (700-Series freezer columns).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Garage-Rated Freezers</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Specifically engineered to handle 0 to 110°F ambient swings</li>
      <li>Have additional thermostat compensation logic plus heater elements (paradoxically, to keep mechanism warm enough to function in cold ambient that confuses standard thermostat)</li>
      <li>Critical for Southern California garages where summer temps hit 100°F+</li>
      <li>Standard freezers in non-rated installations fail unpredictably</li>
      <li>Top brands: Frigidaire FFGFC series, GE garage-ready, Whirlpool garage-ready models</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

